		<div id="comment-1296">
			<cite class="fn">RS-prime</cite>			<a href="http://bloodyshovel.wordpress.com/2012/11/22/the-brain-drain-trap/#comment-1296">November 28, 2012 at 10:28</a>
						<div class="comment-body"><p>&gt; Life at old age is not as good as it could be if there were more young people, but since standard of living is better then the past, old age in China will be as good or better than their recent memory. </p>
<p>It&#8217;s been pointed out before that today&#8217;s elder Chinese has witnessed some pretty serious things in his time, more serious than pop pyramid inversion and corresponding relative poverty. Not only will his life be better than it was in &#8217;95, it will be a lot better than it was in the 60s.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s not the same, but even today&#8217;s elder Japanese at least grew up poor and so is not totally accustomed to high levels of well-being.</p>
